, United Kingdom","White Fryars Churchyard, Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Brockhull, Saltwood, Kent, England":"Saltwood, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Brockhill Manor, Saltwood, Kent, England":"Saltwood, Kent, England","Calehill, Kent, England":"Calehill, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Brockhull was born about 1290, in Calehill, Kent, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir William Thomas Brockhull. He had at least 1 son with Joan Criol Lady of Brockhull. He lived in Saltwood, Kent, England, United Kingdom for about 46 years. In 1384, at the age of 95, his occupation is listed as sheriff to richard ii - thomas brockhull of calehill, in little chart, in the 6th and 7th years. He died in 1390, in Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 101, and was buried in Canterbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1290–1390":"umbes 1290–1390","1290–1390":"1290–1390","1320–1383":"1320–1383","1265–1360":"1265–1360","May 1383":"mai 1383","Abt 1377":"umbes 1377","1320":"1320","1265":"1265","1330":"1330","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","Abt 1290":"umbes 1290","1390":"1390","1290":"1290","Lewes, Sussex, England":"Lewes, Sussex, England","Hythe, Kent, England":"Hythe, Kent, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","White Fryars Churchyard, Canterbury, Kent, England":